                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d19">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/13964: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">at Nanking</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-02-10T14:00:00-05:00"
                            >February 10, 1937—2 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>35. Your 59, February 4, 2 p.m., paragraph 3, last sentence. Department assumes
                    that the officer of the Embassy with whom the informant presumably talked told
                    the informant that of course a report in regard to the American Government’s
                    having taken action of this sort would have no basis in fact.</p>
                <p>When conveying to the Department items of information of this nature, it would be
                    helpful to the Department if the Embassy would add some account of the
                    rejoinders made by the officers of the Embassy to whom the information is
                    communicated.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
